ical contextualisation to productions by the BBC, the Berliner Ensemble, The Katona József Theatre in communist Hungary, the Royal Shakespeare Company, Britain’s National Theatre, The New York Shakespeare Festival, Robert Lepage, Shakespeare’s Globe Theatre and Ralph Fiennes’ major motion picture. This volume will be of interest to a wide range of readers, including specialists, graduate students and undergraduates studying both Coriolanus and the history of Shakespearean performance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aShakespeare 2018. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh  aAlan Howard.  aBertolt Brecht.  aBudapest.  aCoriolanus.  aDominic Dromgoole.  aGlobe theatre.  aLaurence Olivier.  aMargaret Thatcher.  aNational Theatre.  aNew York Shakespeare Festival.  aQuebecois Shakespeare.  aRalph Fiennes.  aRobert Lepage.  aRoyal Shakespeare Company.  aWilliam Shakespeare.  afailed action hero.  agoulash communism.1 aOrmsby, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packagez978311128357940uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610195240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526101952423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526101952/original  a978-3-11-128357-9  Manchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packageb2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles